*Summary*
 the JQL *worklogDate* parameter search filter results are incorrect while using it in combination with *NOT* operator.

*Steps to Reproduce*
 From the Jira Issue Search Advanced Mode launch the following query as examples:

*Example 1:*
{code:java}
not worklogdate > "YYYY/MM/DD" and issue = <YOUR_ISSUE_KEY> 
{code}
 *Example 2:*
{code:java}
not worklogdate > startofday(-10) and issue = <YOUR_ISSUE_KEY>
{code}
Furthermore if we launch the following example query on a test instance:
{code:java}
not worklogdate > "2019/05/15" and issue = TEST-299
{code}
The issue TEST-299 which has his last worklog added on 15/Jun/19 is instead retrieved:

!Screenshot 2019-05-17 at 13.59.53.png|thumbnail!

*Expected Results*
 The expected results would be issues where the the worklog entries date are not > of "YYYY/MM/DD" or not > startofday(-10).

*Actual Results*
 The actual results seems like the operator *worklogdate* is not working when using NOT in front of it: instead of looking for issues which don't have any work logged after a certain date, it is looking for issues for which the first logged date did not occur after a certain date. So basically, instead of looking into any work log in an issue, it is looking for the 1st work log entry which is incorrect.
h3. Workaround

There is a workaround to fix the which consists in avoiding using NOT with the worklogdate operator, but to use an intermediate filter instead:
# First create a filter with the following JQL query:
{code:java}
worklogdate > startofday(-5)
{code}
# Then run the following query by replacing FILTER_ID with the ID of the filter created in the previous step:
{code:java}
filter != FILTER_ID 
{code}

h3. Definition
As per https://www.w3.org/2005/10/howto-favicon, JIRA doesn't comply with the standard HTML format for favicons. In JIRA 8.0, it shows as 
{code}
<link rel="shortcut icon" href="http://example.com/myicon.png">
{code}
for example. However, based on the above link, it should be:
{code}
<link rel="icon" 
      type="image/png" 
      href="http://example.com/myicon.png">
{code}

h3. Suggestion
It would be great if JIRA would follow the standard HTML formatting for favicons.

h3. Summary
When using the [update issue|https://docs.atlassian.com/software/jira/docs/api/REST/7.13.0/#api/2/issue-editIssue] API endpoint to add a comment, Jira fires a webhook and sends the last transition of the issue in the data. This makes the data look as if the issue was just transitioned, which is wrong. 

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Setup webhooks to fire on issue update events.
# Create an issue an transition from status A to status B.
# Update the issue via the API but send a PUT request to */rest/api/2/issue/{issueIdOrKey}* with the data: 
{code:json|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#6A8EB3|bgColor=#F8F8F8}
{"update": {"comment": [{"add": {"body": "Comment body"}}]}}
{code}

h3. Expected Results
The webhook will only be sent the comment info in the body. 

h3. Actual Results
The body includes the transition previously made to the issue as a *changelog* data: 
{code:json|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#6A8EB3|bgColor=#F8F8F8}
  "changelog": {
    "id": "21580937",
    "items": [
      {
        "field": "status",
        "fieldtype": "jira",
        "from": "3",
        "fromString": "In Progress",
        "to": "30897",
        "toString": "AWAITING INFO"
      }
    ]
  }
{code}

h3.Workaround
Use the [Add comment|https://docs.atlassian.com/software/jira/docs/api/REST/7.13.0/#api/2/issue-addComment] endpoint to add comments to issues. This fires the issue updated webhook with the correct data.

